? PATH ? 15
File in the current directory:
When prompted, enter the path to the thread-count text-file that is in the current directory. e.g. if you run the program in the 'Documents' directory, and the text-file is in 'Documents', then simply enter text-file name with its extension. If the file is in another directory that is inside the current directory 'Documents', you must specify this also using:
'<other-directory>/file.txt'.

File outside the current directory:
If the file is in another location from the directory in which you loaded the program, you will need to specify the path to the file from the user path using the '~' key. i.e. you must enter:
'~/<external-directory>/file.txt'.

? CANV ? 24
The canvas is a square, high pixel-density output image displaying the tartan pattern generated by the program on the user's specification.When prompted, you must specify an integral number greater than or equal to 0 for the pixel width and height. A few hundred pixels is ideal, however note that a larger canvas size will take longer to weave, and may cause the device to heat up. The canvas size is capped at scale factor 8, where scale factor is the quotient of the user input canvas size divided by total thread-count size, which is the sum of all the pixel sizes in the thread-count file. 

? THREAD ? 27
The thread-count file contains the pattern and colour information about the tartan, known itself as the thread-count. In each line of the file there are two values separated by a single space. The first value is a key which tells the program which colour to set the square pixel. The second value tells the program what the height/width the pixel should be. The next line describes the next pixel colour and size to go along the sett/half-sett. Note: if the program fails to read the thread-count file, Check that the colour keys are correct and remove any end-of-line (EOL) characters at the bottom of the file. To understand how thread-counts and setts/half-setts work, visit the Scottish Register of Tartan's website:
https://www.tartanregister.gov.uk/threadcount

